snippet: Republicans entered the end of the most expensive midterm campaign in American history confident they will take control of the Senate, but voter interest is low.
abstract: Most expensive midterm campaign in American history is set to end on Election Day with voters' interest at record lows and deep division over what they want government to do in Pres Obama's final two years; Republicans enter final hours confident they will gain at least six seats and take control of Senate.

byline.original: By JONATHAN WEISMAN and ASHLEY PARKER
byline.contributor: Reporting was contributed by Kirk Johnson from Alaska, Nick Corasaniti from Iowa, Katharine Q. Seelye from New Hampshire, John Eligon from Kansas and Jennifer Steinhauer from Kentucky.

lead_paragraph: Republicans entered the end of the most expensive midterm campaign in American history confident they will take control of the Senate, but voter interest is low.

headline.main: On Election’s Eve, G.O.P. Is Confident, but Voters Are Sour
headline.print_headline: G.O.P. Confident on Election’s Eve, With Voters Sour
